<dl id="n36207h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36207h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36207h"> 207(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> showers of blessings ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36207h"><li>FW 552.35f </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36207h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36207h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36207h">MS BL 47484b-456</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:199 <a name="rBd14" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36207h">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Liberal Catholics.]</font> In the Liberal Catholic Church &hellip; ritual is carefully designed with a view to perfecting the spiritual machinery through which <mark>showers of blessings</mark> &hellip; are drawn upon the waiting communicants. &hellip; Every large division of the service makes its contribution towards the completed edifice; one part lays the foundation, another&mdash;just as though it were done by a construction company in the modern business world&mdash;comes along and does its bit, and so on until we have a creamy Santa Sofia which no one can see. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 288</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
